\par If needed, leaving one's posses
sions and assets behind and emigrating elsewhere is a form of worship as stated in the Qur'an. Therefore, Muslims emigrating for the cause of God always see the good in such forced removal from their homes. Indeed, in the Qur'an, those emigrating for the 
cause of God are mentioned among those who can hope for God's Mercy: 
\par 
\par }\pard \s15\qj \li567\ri170\sl-320\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin170\lin567\itap0\pararsid881378 {\b\f0\fs22\lang2057\langfe1055\langnp2057\insrsid4216250\charrsid881378 
Those who have believed and who have migrated and striven for God's sake may expect God's mercy. God is Ever-Forgiving, Most Merciful. (Surat al-Baqara: 218)
\par }\pard \s15\qj \fi567\li0\ri170\sl-320\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin170\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs22\lang2057\langfe1055\langnp2057\insrsid4216250\charrsid881378 
\par The rationale of ignorance 
considers one's fleeing from his home country due to unrest or out of exile to an unfamiliar country as a misfortune, utterly throwing his life into disarray. Yet, it must be mentioned that, believers are, from the outset, aware that they will be disliked
 
by the majority of people who deny the religion of God. Consequently, such an oppression is, in actuality, a manifestation of the truth of the verses of God. That is why believers who emigrate or are driven out of their homes always face such circumstance
s
 with great zeal and anticipation. The superior morality of believers who lived in the time of the Prophet (saas) and their unshakable faith is one of the best examples of today's believers. Aware that obedience to the Prophet (saas) would earn them God's
 pleasure, they willingly endured all forms of hardship with pleasure. For the good of the Muslims, they did not hesitate to leave their country, willingly abandoning all their worldly possessions. 
\par In return for their upstanding morality and the positive way in which they perceived these events, God promised them His infinite Paradise and mercy. Surely, God is true in His promise:
\par 
\par }\pard \s15\qj \li567\ri170\sl-320\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin170\lin567\itap0\pararsid881378 {\b\f0\fs22\lang2057\langfe1055\langnp2057\insrsid4216250\charrsid881378 
Their Lord responds to them: "I will not let the deeds of any doer among you go to waste, male or female-you are both the same 
in that respect. Those who have migrated and were driven from their homes and suffered harm in My Way and fought and were killed, I will erase their bad actions from them and admit them into Gardens with rivers flowing under them, as a reward from God. Th
e best of all rewards is with God." (Surah Al 'Imran: 195)
\par }\pard \s15\qj \fi567\li0\ri170\sl-320\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin170\lin0\itap0 {\f0\fs22\lang2057\langfe1055\langnp2057\insrsid4216250\charrsid881378 
In addition to God's infinite rewards in the Hereafter, God also gives the glad tidings of abundant benefits and resources in this world too. This is recounted in Qur'an as follows: 
\par 
\par }\pard \s15\qj \li567\ri170\sl-320\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin170\lin567\itap0\pararsid881378 {\b\f0\fs22\lang2057\langfe1055\langnp2057\insrsid4216250\charrsid881378 
