\par Although a doctrine going back as far as ancient Greece, the theory of evolution was advanced extensively in the 19th century. The most important development that made the theory the top topic of the world of science was the book by Charles Darwin titled 
}{\i\f0\fs22\lang2057\langfe1055\langnp2057\insrsid4216250\charrsid16134737 The Origin of Species}{\f0\fs22\lang2057\langfe1055\langnp2057\insrsid4216250\charrsid881378 
 published in 1859. In this book, Darwin denied that different living species on the earth were created separately by God. According to Darwin, all living beings had a common ancestor and they diversified over time through small changes. 
\par Darwin's theory was not based on any concrete scientific finding; as he also accepted, it was just an "assumption." Moreover, as Darwin confessed in the long chapter of his book ti
tled "Difficulties of the Theory," the theory was failing in the face of many critical questions. 
\par Darwin invested all his hopes in new scientific discoveries, which he expected to solve the "Difficulties of the Theory." However, contrary to his expectations, scientific findings expanded the dimensions of these difficulties. 
\par The defeat of Darwinism against science can be reviewed under three basic topics:}{\f0\fs22\lang2057\langfe1055\langnp2057\insrsid4216250 
\par }{\f0\fs22\lang2057\langfe1055\langnp2057\insrsid4216250\charrsid881378 
\par 1) The theory can by no means explain how life originated on the earth. 
\par 2) There is no scientific finding showing that the "evolutionary mechanisms" proposed by the theory have any power to evolve at all. 
\par 3) The fossil record proves completely the contrary of the suggestions of the theory of evolution.
\par In this section, we will examine these three basic points in general outlines:
